        IBScore: 5,
        IBComment:
          "Title and Abstract\nThe title is clear and effectively communicates the focus on Sharjah, while also indicating that the study is action research.\nThe abstract requires reformatting, specifically, the removal of centered text. The study emphasizes traditional teaching, with referenced definitions. It connects to the pilot study, describes the use of mixed methods, and highlights key outcomes such as student performance, confidence, engagement, and conceptual clarity. The methodology is also introduced, including the use of focus groups and pre- and post-tests, along with a summary of the main findings.\nIntroduction\nThe introduction outlines definitions of traditional teaching and experiential learning, supported by relevant literature. It takes into account gender considerations and incorporates the researcher's personal experience.\nOn page 9, change “Students” to “students” (lowercase ‘s’).\nJustification and Research Design\nThe study builds on findings from a pilot study, providing a clear justification. It presents two research objectives and clearly articulated research questions. Comparative analysis is included, with consideration of broader conversations and wider educational implications. The thesis follows a clear and logical structure.\n",
        LRScore: 5,
        LRComment:
          'Literature Review\nThe review is underpinned by the theoretical frameworks of Piaget, Kolb, and Bandura, highlighting constructivist experiential learning and social cognitive theory, with strong academic references throughout. It also explores gender differences, comparing the academic performance of boys and girls in inquiry-based and experiential learning contexts. It notes that girls tend to self-evaluate more accurately, while boys often overestimate their performance and are more motivated by competition and engaging activities.\nKids page 16: Children\nExperiential learning is shown to support long-term retention and the development of social-emotional skills, including teamwork and collaborative interaction. Boys are noted to prefer kinaesthetic learning.\nThe literature review identifies a gap: limited research comparing the effects of the same intervention across genders.\nKey terms are defined and properly referenced.\n',
        MScore: 5,
        MComment:
          'Methodology\nThe methodology section provides context and emphasizes the importance of a mixed methods approach, supported by references. The research employs quantitative pre- and post-tests with both control and intervention groups. Qualitatively, focus groups were used with participants from both groups.\nOn page 19, remove the leading O from author.\nThe literature supports the chosen methods, and their justification is provided. The action research design is described and referenced, with classroom observations used to measure engagement, behaviour, and motivation. The pilot study is discussed in detail, along with adjustments made for the main study based on its outcomes.\nParticipants and Ethics\nThe study involved 52 male 6th-grade students, divided into two groups. Ethical considerations are clearly addressed. The study ensures validity and reliability, referencing triangulation, trustworthiness, and transferability.\n',
        RAScore: 5,
        RAComment:
          'Data Analysis\nQuantitative data analysis was conducted using Excel, while qualitative data was analyzed thematically.\nThe results chapter is divided into two sections: quantitative and qualitative findings. Data is presented using clear graphs—note: ensure all graph screenshots are uniform in size. Box plots are explained thoroughly, including their relevance in the context of the study. Data is comprehensively analyzed and connected to the theoretical framework.\nQualitative findings are categorized by theme and supported with participant quotes, along with interpretation of the qualitative data.\nNote: Write “lab” in full—do not abbreviate. Avoid starting sentences with “and” or “but.”\nThe study includes findings from both the control group and the experimental group. Ensure titles/heading are clearly labelled as a and b , respectively. I think rather than numbers.\n',
        DScore: 5,
        DComment:
          'Discussion\nThe discussion cross-references the findings with relevant literature and theoretical frameworks. The results show that boys in the study experienced improved performance, motivation, and confidence. The researcher offers explanations and compares these outcomes with those of female students.\nThe term “survey” on pages 42 and 43 should be replaced with “focus group.”\nThere should be direct references to Appendices C, D, and E. The implications for stakeholders are well-articulated.\n',
        CRScore: 5,
        CRComment:
          'Conclusion and Recommendations\nThe conclusion and recommendations are clear and grounded in literature. They focus on key areas such as engagement, performance, confidence, and conceptual understanding. The section also discusses opportunities and challenges, particularly in terms of gender-based comparisons.\nKey findings indicate greater improvement among male students. The study’s limitations are acknowledged. The conclusion is strongly rooted in the theories of experiential learning and constructivism, as well as concepts of critical thinking and self-efficacy. A robust and up-to-date range of academic references is included, with an emphasis on peer-reviewed journals.\n',
        OOScore: 4,
        OOComment:
          '•\tAbstract formatting. Remove centered text and ensure it follows standard layout.\n•\tHeadings in Results. Label as a and b (rather than using numbers) for clarity and consistency.\n•\tDirect references to appendices. Ensure the main text clearly points to Appendices C, D, and E.\n•\tGraph presentation. All graph screenshots should be uniform in size for visual consistency.\n',
